},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm4.staticflickr.com/3865/15065531386_18d0b5926b_z.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1,"offset":1609},"end":{"line":16,"column":70,"offset":1678}}},{"type":"text","value":"The Luo Brothers, Welcome the World Famous Brand Name, 1993-94","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":70,"offset":1678},"end":{"line":16,"column":132,"offset":1740}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1,"offset":1609},"end":{"line":16,"column":132,"offset":1740}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The Luo Brothers","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":3,"offset":1744},"end":{"line":18,"column":19,"offset":1760}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1,"offset":1742},"end":{"line":18,"column":21,"offset":1762}}},{"type":"text","value":": Classified as Political Pop, these three brothers from Beijing mock the Eastern consumption of Western brands (such as Coca-cola) by incorporating acid colors, impish Chinese babies and depictions of Chairman Mao.","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":21,"offset":1762},"end":{"line":18,"column":236,"offset":1977}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1,"offset":1742},"end":{"line":18,"column":236,"offset":1977}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"https://farm4.staticflickr.com/3887/14901940510_f246dbe5d5_z.jpg","alt":null},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1,"offset":1982},"end":{"line":21,"column":70,"offset":2051}}},{"type":"text","value":"Sun Yuan and Peng Yu, Old Persons Home, 2007","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":70,"offset":2051},"end":{"line":21,"column":114,"offset":2095}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1,"offset":1982},"end":{"line":21,"column":114,"offset":2095}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Sun Yuan & Peng Yu","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":3,"offset":2099},"end":{"line":23,"column":21,"offset":2117}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1,"offset":2097},"end":{"line":23,"column":23,"offset":2119}}},{"type":"text","value":": These guys a probably my favorite collective because they’re the most outlandish and may be the “most controversial artists working in China today” (says multiple sources). This duo based in Beijing, deals with conceptual art and work in installation and performance art. They’ve incorporated live animals (fish, crustations, dogs), baby cadavers, among other things in their works. In ","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":23,"offset":2119},"end":{"line":23,"column":411,"offset":2507}}},{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Old Persons Home,","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":412,"offset":2508},"end":{"line":23,"column":429,"offset":2525}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":411,"offset":2507},"end":{"line":23,"column":430,"offset":2526}}},{"type":"text","value":" shown at the Saatchi Gallery in London, the duo used motorized wheelchairs with hyperrealistic silicon sculptures made in the likeness of elderly folks who were supposed to represent the U.N. (dead). The wheelchairs were placed on an automatic setting at a very low speed and were sent on a collision course, bumper-car style.","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":430,"offset":2526},"end":{"line":23,"column":757,"offset":2853}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1,"offset":2097},"end":{"line":23,"column":757,"offset":2853}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So what I’m trying to explore here is what exactly is achieved through collaborative efforts by these artists working in a post-Cultural Revolution, post-Mao, post-open trade contemporary China. As a point of comparison, I will also incorporate works by Russian and Western collectives. I originally wanted to explore Chinese art because contemporary art is taught (at least in my program) as being fairly Western-centric and while BRIC (Brazil, Russia, India and China) and MINT (Mexico, Indonesia, Nigeria and Turkey) countries are incorporated to a small extent, there are tremendous gaps in my knowledge about Chinese contemporary art. The idea for my thesis was also spurred by the premise that Burning Man was founded on– the idea of working together to produce art instead of perpetuating the artist as genius idea.","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1,"offset":2855},"end":{"line":25,"column":823,"offset":3677}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1,"offset":2855},"end":{"line":25,"column":823,"offset":3677}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1,"offset":0},"end":{"line":25,"column":823,"offset":3677}}}}